<TITLE> Australian openers survive morning session </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 LONDON, Aug 21 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - Australia openers Simon Katich and Shane Watson repelled a hostile assault from the England fast bowlers on the second morning of the fifth Ashes Test at The Oval on Friday. After dismissing England for 332 in their first innings, Australia reached 61 for no wicket when rain forced the players off the field four minutes before the scheduled lunch interval in a match the home side must win to regain the Ashes. Andrew Flintoff, in his last Test, bowled with great spirit from the Pavilion end and had two vociferous lbw appeals against Watson rejected by umpire Asad Rauf with the batsman beaten for pace. Watson was also beaten outside the off-stump by James Anderson while Katich took 14 balls to get off the mark. Katich relieved the pressure with two boundaries in an over from Anderson and England captain Andrew Strauss turned to off-spinner Graeme Swann to see if he could find the sharp turn Australia's Marcus North occasionally extracted on Thursday. Swann got one delivery to jag sharply away from Katich and Steve Harmison, replacing Flintoff, hit the left-hander on the body. Katich was uncertain outside the off-stump against Harmison, who bowled a challenging line, and Swann spun a delivery past the groping Watson but for all their efforts England could not break through against the gritty Australian pair. After play resumed on Friday, James Anderson, who had gone a England record 54 Tests without a duck, lasted only six balls before he was lbw to Ben Hilfenhaus without scoring. Stuart Broad, on 26 overnight, survived a difficult chance to Mitchell Johnson at long-leg off Peter Siddle. He reached 37 before becoming Hilfenhaus' third victim, caught at second slip by Ricky Ponting. Harmison extended his Oval Test average to 131 with 12 not out. All his runs came in bounda
